{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480618"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:47:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:47:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"86"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"86","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/86"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.23,0.05,0.42,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"86"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45114"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"86","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/86"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"86"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29979"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3810"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11634"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11635"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/45114"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man presents with a five month history of abdominal discomfort. He feels full before completing his usual meals and has consequently lost some weight. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus diagnosed 15 years ago and this is managed with metformin. He has never smoked but enjoys a few cans of beer each night. On examination his blood pressure is 132/76 mmHg, pulse 76/min, respiratory rate 17/min and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. A triphasic abdominal CT scan shows a 2cm liver lesion that is hypodense on arterial phase and has increased contrast uptake on portal venous and delayed phases (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abscess","Haemangioma","Adenoma","Hepatocellular carcinoma","Metastatic liver disease"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ELiver metastases are among the most common liver tumours and approximately 25-50% of people who die with a malignancy have liver involvement.\u00a0A CT scan is the preferred imaging of suspected liver metastases, which show a characteristic pattern of hypoattenuating on arterial phase with peripheral enhancement. Central filling-in may be seen on the portal venous phase and the delayed phase may show washout. This is helpful in determining a metastasis from a haemangioma, which shows irregular filling-in during the delayed phase.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pattern of contrast uptake on this CT scan is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Emetastatic liver disease\u003C/strong\u003E and this could be from a primary malignancy in the gastrointestinal tract, considering his age and nature of his symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst rim enhancement on delayed post-contrast images can be seen with hepatocellular carcinoma, these tumours tend to have a more nodular appearance, with varying patterns of enhancement due to necrosis, fat and /or calcification.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A liver lesion that is hypodense on the arterial phase of a contrast-enhanced CT scan is very likely to malignant."],"references":["Honda Y, Higaki T, Higashihori H, Monzen Y, Tatsugami F, Date S, et al. Re-evaluation of detectability of liver metastases by contrast-enhanced CT: added value of hepatic arterial phase imaging. Japanese Journal of Radiology. 2014;32(8):467-75."]},"relationships":